segments.text: I guess, in other words, the jobs will be here for the people who moved in, whereas in the past, those jobs have not been here.
We have 8,000 jobs, plus probably 1,000 construction jobs.
So it's 9,000 jobs and probably 10,000 or 12,000 houses.
So we almost have a job for every dwelling unit.
And a third of the people who live here work here.
OK, I was wondering what the numbers were.
And the other 2 thirds, a third will go downtown, and the other third scatters.

uh and i don't think we'll probably ever get much more than half but i think then that when people commute out of here downtown somebody will be commuting in from yeah philadelphia that's okay yeah what about your transportation though is the future of transportation in this i mean to the outside world airports the uh we have a cold road yeah we have uh you know the woodlands express
which is an excellent bus system from our park and ride lot, which has just been expanded, I think, to 800 or 1,000 cars.
And there's vans and buses leave from there every morning for people who leave their car here and do want to park in.
Are you all talking rail service at all through here at all?
Yeah.
Rail takes the kind of density that we don't have out here and probably won't have.
Is that right?
I mean, if they did a high-speed rail from Dallas to Houston and had a stop right here at I-45, I'm sure some people would get on and go downtown.
But it would not be supported.
No, rail is pretty restricted, unless you've got a density like New York or downtown Atlanta or something.
I don't know.
Missouri caught the train.
The airport caught the train to town.
Europe said, we're not going to spend our money.
It's an incredible world.
It is, and it could be here.
It could be here.
It may not be where we want.
This city spends $1 billion a year in the Houston area fixing up highways so people can get out one car at a time and drive back and forth.
If they took some of that billion dollars a year of new highway construction or refurbished highways or widened highways or fixed the bridges and devoted it to rail and spent the money on rail,
But again, the accountant mentality says if you're going to have a rail, it's got to pay for itself.
Yeah, right.
Well, the highway construction isn't paying for itself.
That's right.
Yeah, the automobile industry is one of the most subsidized industries in the country in that sense.
You give them a free place to drive.
If you gave the railroad company free tracks, then people probably could afford to ride on the train.
But you want them to buy the land, build the tracks, run the things,
And you won't give them a subsidy, you want them to make a profit.
Well, that's a pretty poor business, it turns out.
Now there's an alternative.
Before there were cars, of course, railroads were wonderfully profitable for everybody, because you either got on the train or you rode your horse.
So you got on the train.
The railroaders made a lot of money.
I've got a couple of questions that are really different.
How does your job as planner and
George, or we've been told, or at least have been given the impression that George Mitchell is something of a visionary in terms of the development of the Woodlands.
How do you work together, or how does that come together, his vision, if that's, you know, if you would do that?
George has gone to Europe and seen new towns.
George came to Columbia, Maryland, saw what we did there.
George envisioned doing a community here that was done right.
Right yet to be defined.
He liked what we all said when we started planning it and what right would be.
And he supported it with hard cash and staff against lots of critics who said this wasn't the way to invest his money.
In fact, we lost one company president
the energy division and said, let's just stick in energy and I don't want to have anything to do with real estate.
Well, I do, because I think we should put back into America some of what we're taking out.
And I've always said this on George's behalf, that I think that he wants the Woodlands to be a role model for how the next America could be built in the next centuries.
that instead of sprawling subdivisions around the urban centers of America, you could have new communities that take a lesson from the environment that's created here.
We have the opportunity, and it's still to be undertaken, but we have people growing up in this lifestyle, and it ought to be measured against maybe 1960, where you got suburban sprawl,
traffic congestion, ugly signs.
I mean, what about the health and well-being of the people in that spot versus here?
Is there really a difference?
Are people more sick in one place or the other?
Or is there stress on the human condition?
One of the things I say, our environment reduces the stress on the human condition.
It leaves you with a reservoir that makes you able better to cope with the other things, marital stress, job stress.
children's stress.

But on top of all of those stresses, your stress getting to and from work gets visually bombarded with blight and ugliness and traffic congestion and the insecurity of, like you say, people live five blocks in of 1960 and it goes for 20 blocks.
And they sit in their house and the cars come and go.
They don't know who the hell's in the car.
They see a car parked in the street and say, whose car is that?
I don't recognize that car.
You take somebody to the woodlands and they sit on their cul-de-sac and everybody knows whose car belongs there.
There's nobody running by that they have to worry about.
You've taken some anxiety off their security issue.
Those things may all add up and be meaningful.
I don't know.
Somebody's got to measure that.
Maybe you need to take 10,000 or 20,000 people to the woodlands in that geographic area and compare it with 20,000 people in the 1960 area.
Those are both come off
off the I-45 corridor, same distance in from downtown, and measure what's happening between those two groups of people.
Anything significant?
I don't know.
That would be a delightful cross project to do.
How does the, what I'm trying to get at though, is how does the synergy of the woodlands develop?
In other words, does Mr. Mitchell have concept, idea, image?
Do you then take concept, idea, image, and as you say, hardline it?
Or in fact, did you create concept, idea, and image from something much more hazy?
In other words, how does it develop?
I think George Mitchell
He was one of the most remarkable guys I've ever met in my life.
I had my own company for 25 years.
I said I would be crazy to ever sell my company and go to work for somebody else.
But George Smith was probably one of the few people in the country I would do that for.
He had the concept of the Houston Advanced Research Center pulling together the universities to get grant research going, to get technology going.
in Texas instead of having it go to Massachusetts and California and everything.
Do creative ideas here.
He envisioned and made it happen.
He envisioned building a model community here and he went and visited a whole bunch of them, including Columbia and Irvine.
And he got the people who were responsible for both and brought them, brought us here and said, let's, let's do it right.
Let's, you know,
Here are the tools it takes.
And he's been supportive of doing it.
When I told him we needed a pavilion, we agreed.
And back in 83, we spent $350,000 doing early planning studies.
We put his money where the idea was.
He said, yes, we do need it.
And then he and Cynthia got together and said, let's, when the recession was over here, he said, let's get Dick to get the pavilion going again.
And we started out very modestly, like, how about $1 million?
How about $4 million?
Well, we're up to $10 million.
And we're still going.
We've got another half a million in next year.
I think it's going to get better every year.
He has great faith and vision in that he's building for things that will be far beyond his lifetime.
And he cares about that.
I don't know if you know what he's doing in Galveston.
I've been reading about it.
He's almost single-handedly saving that island from the doldrums.
He's brought back the Strand to the grandeur of the 1890s.
Are you involved in any of that?
My vice president for planning.
I've given him the Galveston project because I'm
than what I have to do here in the Colorado project.
Are you doing a ski area?
That's great.
It's exciting.
It's obvious that the Woodlands Corporation, which Mr. Richmond enjoined us to call it rather than just the Woodlands, is also branching out into other areas beyond the Woodlands.
Well, we have 60,000 acres of real estate, and 25 of it is the Woodlands.
So we've got more real estate outside the Woodlands.
Some of it is what I call Woodlands 2, and some of Woodlands is west of here.
You know, somebody will do it in the next century, but the market's not there yet until we're built out, and then they can go do another one, or a smaller one.
But we happen to have 1,800 acres near Aspen, which we developed into what's called Owl Creek.
And while I was up doing that, as project director for that, I found this property of 3,200 acres near Steamboat Springs and convinced George we should
buy into that and create a joint venture with the Steamboat Ski Area to do a total resort, year-round resort there with a major ski mountain and there's a 500-acre lake on it.
Great golf potential and so forth for the resort community.
And the Mitchell companies and now the Woodlands Corporation does a lot of resort properties.
We have Cape Royale up at Lake Livingston.
We have Point Venture at Lake Travis.
We've got
several projects down in Galveston, the Galveston Country Club, Pirates Beach, Sunbird.
But we do a lot of resort type communities.
So the Lake Catamount project, although that's really the biggest one, is also a resort.
So that's not a new word for us.
We use the building in running golf courses and resort hotels and second home communities.
So that's kind of second nature to us, whether we can
carry Lake Catamount forward.
Yet or not, I don't know.
I've gotten zoning there for nearly 4,000 dwelling units.
We've got a ski mountain for 12,000 skiers a day.
And we're in the final throes of a four-year environmental impact statement.
Of course, the $1.5 million worth of studies, we'll know by Christmas whether we've got it.
Are you adjoining national forest lands or anything?
Yeah, the ski area is on the national forest lands.
And it's taken four years to get through there.
But anyway, I'm sure you can tell I really believe that we have a statement here that's worthy of national attention.
I think what we're doing in creating environments for lives is an advancement of our civilization.
If we could only spread these goals and how to achieve them,
so that more developers would band together and do bigger, more diverse-type projects where you could put together the bits and pieces to have a society.
You know, we've got churches here.
George has put in a private school that's at another dimension.
We have daycare centers.
We've got 41 lakes we've built so far here.
We're all very natural in respecting the environment and enhancing the environment.
Our wildflower program, which George insists on funding, again, why do you want to spend $35,000 every year on wildflower seeds?
But we want this place in the spring to be awash with flowers.
It's just another way of man and nature enjoying one another.
The color here in the spring is just gorgeous.
Well, it should be interesting to see if this, in fact, becomes a prototype for it.
Yeah.
Well, I think it will.
It'll always be honored for being a better place in Houston to live.
Yeah, right, nothing else.
And I worry a little bit because I grew up next to Radburn, New Jersey, which was done by Clarence Stein, an architect out of New York in the early 30s, and it fell during the Depression.
And it still has a waiting list of people to get in.
It never got finished because it went bankrupt, but they had open space and pathways and parks.
similar to what we have in our villages, as a matter of fact.
And I can read here, if you think the woodlands is good, you can go to Tapiola in Finland outside of Helsinki and see a new town that was built in the 50s.
It's every bit as good as what we've done.
And that's a poor country, Finland.
And so people do.
There is a common denominator between the different cultures of people.
given the opportunity, we'll produce the same kind of thing.

Socio-economic mix of housing in the forest, close to nature, providing stimulation, providing recreation, providing education, giving people a chance to optimize their environment and the quality of their lives.
And it's sad to see that 99% of the housing that gets built in the United States is just shelters being thrown on 20 acres here and 40 acres there.
and we spread people in a thin veneer across the countryside without any pattern or organization of their life support systems.
It's really cruel, and that's why the New Communities Act was such a fine idea.
Why can't we organize the economic and demographic forces of this country such that we promote community development instead of suburban sprawl bedroom communities?
That's not right.
We can do better than that.
The environments that we're studying so hard now to put on a space platform are what we should be doing for our everyday living.
Why don't we put the same effort into that as we are for spacewalking or space orbit, orbital living?
Probably we're going to learn things up there that will bring back that.
Well, they are learning the psychology of living, I guess, and part of what's going on.
That's exactly right.
That's a very good overview.
Don, do you have any other thoughts we ought to...
Put yourself in our shoes for a minute, or whoever's shoes you may be wearing.
One of the things that Mr. Mitchell wanted us to do was to concentrate on the last six to eight years and the future.
What events, what ideas, what developments,
initiatives are going to matter the most that have happened in the last half dozen, eight, ten years?
Okay, the creation of HARC, which is spawning high technology jobs, not only for the Woodland, but for the Houston region, and bringing in bright minds and families to work and live here.
People who are committed and appreciate the quality of life and will help support it.
Creation of a private school,

provide for those same kind of people who are really oriented toward making sure their kids get a jump start toward the technology of the future, which is going to require a lot tougher academic achievement than most people allow their kids to get away without.
I think the cultural maturing of the cultural
And the festive side of the woodlands is maturing.
The pavilion has been a big recent addition to that.
Yeah, it sure has.
We've got a good program.
Yeah.
If I could just summarize.
I have to backtrack a little bit.
Sure.
I think in the last recent years, the most important thing is that PARCC was brought on and has been successful in generating the interest in the university support that it has, and now in research.
and high-quality, high-tech jobs in industry and the development of industries for the future.

But the venture capital group that was formed, again, with Georgia's seed money that now takes some of that research and finds the commercially viable projects and spawns new companies, creates new jobs, which some of them might take off and be really important to the Houston and Texas economy.
I think the private school adds a dimension to help attract the finer minds.
You know, at Park they're doing particle research and laser research and things that are at the front edge of where our society is going, technically, and the computer setup that they have there.
Those things are all fantastic.

And then simple things like interfaith and the religious community that's evolved in the Woodlands and all the churches and the fact that the school system has supported us in adding schools as they're needed.
And I used to say also another important thing, too, is we can plan and strive to build an environment or an envelope for people to come and put their lives in.
When we're done, the success of the Woodlands is going to depend a lot
on just who moves here.
Because in the long run, it's the quality of the people that are here and how they work together to build a community and have an allegiance to themselves to make a better place.
And I think we can give them a head start by giving them something that's functionally better.
The people that come here are really important.
I think the future is

is the expansion of the town center, both through the mall, the Lake Robins business complex that's right next to the mall, the canal down to the pavilion, and the kind of generation of cultural, recreational, and commercial activities that can have, which can rival San Antonio in the future, which brings them 12 million visitors a year, where Tivoli Garden in Copenhagen brings
12, 15 million people from Europe during the three or four month summer season.
Our canal from the pavilion to Lake Robins can be a destination place for the whole country to come.
And I think these are things to do for the future that can build in this whole business complex that we really become the northern satellite hub of Houston right here in the wilderness.
That sounds exciting.
We appreciate your time and interview very much.
